erracial union building and worker education during the Great Depression.Investigating why immigrant Jewish unionists in the International Ladies' Garment Workers' Union (ILGWU) appealed to an international force of coworkers, Katz traces their ideology of a working-class based cultural pluralism, which Daniel Katz newly terms "mutual culturalism," back to the revolutionary experiences of Russian Jewish women. These militant women and their male allies constructed an ethnic identity derived from Yiddish socialist tenets based on the principle of autonomous national cultures in the late nineteenth century Russian Empire. Built on original scholarship and bolstered by exhaustive research, All Together Different offers a fresh perspective on the nature of ethnic identity and working-class consciousness and contributes to current debates about the origins of multiculturalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jun 2020) 0aClothing tradezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCollective bargainingxClothing industryzUnited States. 0aJewish labor unionszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aJewsxEmploymentzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewsxPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszUnited StatesxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 0aMulticulturalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorking classxPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814763674423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814763674.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSH